solutions.content:
**This is a pretty easy question once you understand the main concept and how all the data structures work together. I will be focusing mailny on the concept part of this.**

**There are 3 crutial parts to this question.**
* Pre-Processed Wordlist.
* Making the Graph.
* BFS and keep track of levels.

**Data Structures.**
* unordered_map<string, bool> visited;
* unordered_map<string, int> level;
* unordered_map<string, vector\<string\> \> same; ( generic value )
* unordered_map\<string, vector\<string\> \> G; ( main Graph )
* queue<string> Q; ( for BFS )

Lets look into each part in detail.

------

**Pre-Processed Wordlist**

lets take a small example - 
```
startWord = "hit"
endWord   = "dot"
wordList  = ["hot", "dot"]
```

Now is take each word and consider their **Generic Form**.By replacing each character with '*'.
Eg: `hit => [*it, h*t, hi*]`

Then we construct the 1<sup>st</sup> map that will contain 
* Key as the Generic Form.
* Value is a vector of strings theat have the same Generic Form.

For the above example the map is as follows : 

![Generic](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/66634743/88387158-f8d0bb80-cdc2-11ea-9197-6a0f77d27861.png)

Notice that there are **unwanted edges**(The ones with vector size = 1)
For the main example the the map (ignoring the unwanted edges) is as follows:

```text
do* | dot, dog
*ot | hot, dot, lot
lo* | lot, log
*og | dog, log, cog
h*t | hot, hit
```

------

**Making the Graph**

Once we perform the pre-computation and make the map, we can easily construct the graph of the related words.

We just iterate over the pre-computed map and insert into the main map for those values where the `vector size > 1`.

For the main example the map is as follows :

![Graph](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/66634743/88387156-f79f8e80-cdc2-11ea-841b-b85c253d43f6.png)


```text
hit | hot
cog | dog, log,
dog | dot, log, cog
dot | dog, hot, lot
hot | dot, lot, hit
lot | hot, dot, log
log | lot, dog, cog
```

------

**BFS and keep track of levels**

This is the Heart of the Program but also the most trivial.

Few things to keep in mind
* Keep track of the levels.
* Keep visited to avoid loops.

To keep track of levels i have used this logic : [GFG levels](https://www.***.org/level-node-tree-source-node-using-bfs/)

> If you are curious how the **level map** looks like :

```
level => 
cog | 5     <- found it :)
log | 4
hot | 2
hit | 1
dog | 4
dot | 3
lot | 3
```
This contains the levels of all the words in the list. 

**Complete Code**
```
int ladderLength(string beginWord, string endWord, vector<string>& wordList) 
    {
        // check if endWord is in wordList
        if(find(wordList.begin(), wordList.end(), endWord) == wordList.end()) return 0;

        wordList.push_back(beginWord);

        // Different Data Structures.
        unordered_map<string, bool> visited;
        unordered_map<string, int> level;
        unordered_map<string, vector<string> > same, G;
        queue<string> Q;

        // Pre-Processed Wordlist
        for(string s : wordList)
        {
            string word = s;
            for(int i=0;i<s.size();++i)
            {
                s[i] = '*';                // change the ith letter to '*'
                same[s].push_back(word);   // push into the map
                s[i] = word[i];            // replace the ith char to the original char 
            }

            visited[word] = false;         // initialize visited[] in the same loop
        }

        // Making the Graph
        for(auto i : same)
        {
            int size = i.second.size();
            if(size == 1) continue;

            for(int j=0;j<size-1;++j)
                for(int k=j+1;k<size;++k)
                {
                    G[i.second[j]].push_back(i.second[k]);
                    G[i.second[k]].push_back(i.second[j]);
                }
        }

        // BFS and keep track of levels
        Q.push(beginWord);
        visited[beginWord] = true;
        level[beginWord] = 1;

        while(!Q.empty())
        {
            string curr = Q.front();
            Q.pop();

            for(string i : G[curr])
            {
                if(!visited[i])
                {
                    Q.push(i);
                    level[i] = level[curr] + 1;
                    visited[i] = true;

                    if(i == endWord) return level[endWord];
                }
            }
        }

        return 0;
    }
```

