**Why BFS ?**
* Since we are looking for **shortest transformation sequence**, if makes a lot more sense to go **level by level** i.e. BFS.
* In general opt for level order if you are looking for shortest path as it requires lesser time.

**Problem**
We have to go from **beginWord** to **endWord** by changing **1 character** in beginWord at a time such that new word formed must present in **wordList**(given in question). And we have to return minimum number from transformation in beginWord to reach endWord.

**Example**

beginWord = "hit"
endWord = "cog"
wordList = ["hot","dot","dog","lot","log","cog"]

	lv 1-					hit = beginWord
							 |
	lv 2-    				hot
						 /       \
	lv 3-   		  dot         lot
			         / 
	lv 4-       dog
				/
	lv 5-    cog = endWord

**Hence answer is 5 that is the number of level in BFS.**
Note that every word in tree in **present in WordList** provided in question and we are changing **one character at a time**.

Try making trees couple of times and you will get it

Go through comments for better understanding

**Code**

```
class Solution {
public:
    int ladderLength(string beginWord, string endWord, vector<string>& wordList)
    {
        unordered_set<string> s;  // set to know possible words to visit

		bool flag = false; // flag to check if endWord is present in wordlist or not
        for(auto i:wordList)
        {
            s.insert(i);  // insert words from wordlist to set
            if(i==endWord)flag=true;    
        }

		// if endWord is not present in wordlist
		// we cant go from startWord to endWord
		// in short you cannot travel without a destination :)
        if(flag==false)return 0;

		// rest is simple BFS

        queue<string> q; // queue for performing bfs 
        q.push(beginWord); // starting from startword
        int depth = 0; // depth is basically level which we have to return

        while(!q.empty())
        {
            depth++; // incrementing level
            int lsize=q.size(); // size of current level
            while(lsize--) // process current level
            {
                string temp = q.front(); //current word
                q.pop();

                for(int i=0;i<temp.size();++i)
                {
                    string copy = temp; // copy of current word
                    for(char c='a';c<='z';++c) // try every char a-z
                    {
                        copy[i]=c; // make change in at ith position
                        if(copy==temp)continue; // if same then move on
                        if(copy==endWord)return depth+1; // if reached endWord return level+1

						// if changed word is valid(present in set) 
						if(s.find(copy)!=s.end()) 
                        {
                            q.push(copy);//  then add it in queue
                            s.erase(copy);// remove it from valid as it is already used
                        }
                    }
                }
            }
        }
		 // if not found in bfs
		 // then it is not possible to go from startWord to endWord
		 // hence return zero
        return 0;
    }
};
```

