so if you are having tle here are somethings you can try before jumping to the answer
1.try bfs,don't use dfs you will just end up spending same intial path before which graph branch of multiple time and here goal isn't to reach the goal is to reach efficiently, here it is explained more beautifully kudos for the visuals https://leetcode.com/problems/word-ladder/discuss/2634411/Here-is-Why-DP-DFS-fails-with-Memoization.-44th-test-case-failing.
2.use hashset it will do traversal in O(1)
3.actually you don't need N^2 to make graph, here 26*x*K*x*N is much cheaper.
4.use stringbuilder or chararray for string manipulation.
5.the removal of word from set should be done as soon as word is added into queue,the word you are dealing with will come after a lot of word which already exist in the queue and some of those words might end up traversing it again and adding it again to the queue.
```
class Solution {
    public int ladderLength(String beginWord, String endWord, List<String> wordList) {
        HashSet<String> set=new HashSet<>();
        Queue<Pair> q=new LinkedList<>();
        for(int i=0;i<wordList.size();i++)set.add(wordList.get(i));
        // set.remove(beginWord); //don't delay it to here.
        q.add(new Pair(beginWord,1));
        while(!q.isEmpty()){
            Pair p=q.poll();
            String word=p.str;
            set.remove(word);
            if(word.equals(endWord)) return p.price;
            if(word.length()!=beginWord.length()) continue;
            for(int i=0;i<word.length();i++){
                StringBuilder sb=new StringBuilder(word);
                for(int j=0;j<26;j++){
                    sb.setCharAt(i,(char)(97+j));
                    if(set.contains(sb.toString())){
                        set.remove(sb.toString());//implement right here.
                        q.add(new Pair(sb.toString(),p.price+1));
                    }
                }
            }
        }
        return 0;
    }
}
